  "local_port": 35046,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, **\"ng\"** and **\"nang\"** are distinct in usage despite their similar pronunciation. Here\u2019s a structured breakdown of their rules:\n\n### **NG** (Object/Possessive Marker)\n1. **Possession**  \n   - Equivalent to \"of\" or the possessive **\u2019s** in English.  \n   - Example:  \n     - *Bahay **ng** guro* \u2192 \"Teacher\u2019s house\"  \n     - *Kotse **ng** kaibigan* \u2192 \"Friend\u2019s car\"\n\n2. **Direct Object Marker**  \n   - Introduces the object of a verb.  \n   - Example:  \n     - *Kumain **ng** kanin* \u2192 \"Ate rice\"  \n     - *Bumili **ng** libro* \u2192 \"Bought a book\"\n\n---\n\n### **NANG** (Adverbial/Clausal Connector)\n1. **Adverbs of Manner**  \n   - Describes **how** an action is done.  \n   - Example:  \n     - *Tumakbo **nang** mabilis* \u2192 \"Ran quickly\"  \n     - *Sumayaw **nang** malakas* \u2192 \"Danced energetically\"\n\n2. **Repetition or Intensity**  \n   - Reduplicated verbs for emphasis or repeated action.  \n   - Example:  \n     - *Tumawa **nang** tumawa* \u2192 \"Laughed repeatedly\"  \n     - *Umiyak **nang** umiyak* \u2192 \"Cried intensely\"\n\n3. **Time/Result Clauses**  \n   - Means **\"when\"** (past events) or **\"so that\"**.  \n   - Example:  \n     - ***Nang** dumating siya, umalis ako* \u2192 \"**When** he arrived, I left\"  \n     - *Nag-aral siya **nang** mabuti para pumasa* \u2192 \"He studied hard **so that** he\u2019d pass\"\n\n4. **Questions with \"Gaano\" or \"Ilan\"**  \n   - Used in adverbial questions.  \n   - Example:  \n     - *Gaano katagal **nang** ka dito?* \u2192 \"How long **have** you been here?\"\n\n---\n\n### Key Differences\n| **NG**                          | **NANG**                          |\n|----------------------------------|-----------------------------------|\n| Marks possession/objects        | Introduces adverbs/clauses       |\n| *Kumain **ng** mansanas*        | *Tumakbo **nang** mabilis*       |\n| *Sapatos **ng** bata*           | *Nang matapos, umuwi kami*       |\n\n### Common Mistakes to Avoid\n- **Incorrect**: *Kumain ako **nang** kanin* \u2192 \"I ate rice\" (should use **ng**).  \n- **Correct**: *Kumain ako **ng** kanin **nang** mabilis* \u2192 \"I ate rice quickly.\"\n\nBy mastering these distinctions, you\u2019ll enhance your Tagalog fluency! \ud83c\udf1f",
